  urldate = {2026-03-07},
  abstract = {Version 4.0 of the Gravitational-Wave Transient Catalog (GWTC-4.0) adds new candidates detected by the LIGO, Virgo, and KAGRA observatories through the first part of the fourth observing run (O4a: 2023 May 24 15:00:00 to 2024 January 16 16:00:00 UTC) and a preceding engineering run. In this new data, we find 128 new compact binary coalescence candidates that are identified by at least one of our search algorithms with a probability of astrophysical origin \$p\_\{\textbackslash rm astro\} \textbackslash geq 0.5\$ and that are not vetoed during event validation. We also provide detailed source property measurements for 86 of these that have a false alarm rate \${$<$} 1 \textbackslash rm\{yr\}\textasciicircum\{-1\}\$. Based on the inferred component masses, these new candidates are consistent with signals from binary black holes and neutron star-black hole binaries (GW230518\_125908 and GW230529\_181500). Median inferred component masses of binary black holes in the catalog now range from \$5.79\textbackslash,M\_\textbackslash odot\$ (GW230627\_015337) to \$137\textbackslash,M\_\textbackslash odot\$ (GW231123\_135430), while GW231123\_135430 was probably produced by the most massive binary observed in the catalog. For the first time we have discovered binary black hole signals with network signal-to-noise ratio exceeding 30, GW230814\_230901 and GW231226\_01520, enabling high-fidelity studies of the waveforms and astrophysical properties of these systems. Combined with the 90 candidates included in GWTC-3.0, the catalog now contains 218 candidates with \$p\_\{\textbackslash rm astro\} \textbackslash geq 0.5\$ and not otherwise vetoed, doubling the size of the catalog and further opening our view of the gravitational-wave Universe.},
